               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate notBefore="1881" notAfter="1899" evidence="prosopography"/>
                     The following bishops are mentioned in the supplication formulas: 
                     <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS7830Petros"><t:roleName xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="title">ʾAbbā</t:roleName> Ṗeṭros IV</persName> (<locus target="#20v"/>), who died in <date>1917</date>, 
                     <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS6876Matewos"><t:roleName xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="title">ʾAbbā</t:roleName> Mātewos</persName> (<locus target="#21r #22r"/>), who died in <date>1926</date>, 
                     <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS6404Luqas"><t:roleName xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="title">ʾAbbā</t:roleName> Luqās</persName> (<locus target="#22r"/>), who died in <date>1899</date>.
                     All of them came to Ethiopia in <date>1881</date>.
                     The name of <persName role="patron" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS12965SayfaMi">Sayfa Mikāʾel</persName> is frequently mentioned in the supplication formulas 
                     throughout the manuscript. His name is written in the main hand. This strongly suggests that he was the patron or the original owner of the manuscript.
                     The name of <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS12966WaldaM"><t:roleName xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="title">Mam(h)ǝru</t:roleName> Walda Māryām</persName> is written in 
                     a secondary hand on <locus target="#41v"/>, perhaps in the same hand as that of the interlineal signs. He was either a later owner or donor of the manuscript.
                  </origin>
               </history>
          
